column2:
I didn’t buy anything.

  • nothing (with neg. verbs); not any
    (Expression; Adverb)

#何物なにもの:
  • something
    (Noun)
  • nothing (with neg. verb)
  • Other Forms　何ものなにもの

(with neg. verb)

column2:
I miss ramen.
- 恋しい is only used for things, not for people.
#恋しいこいしい:
  • yearned for; longed for; missed
    (I-adjective)

I don't want to work.
- GT: "Don't want to work"
- 仕事した - worked, shigoto + suru (past tense)
- 仕事したい - want to work + negation くない because behaves like an i-adjective
- argh... it's 仕事したくない

column1: 見なかった、見ていない・見ませんでした、見ていません
column2:
Didn’t see it, didn’t see it YET
- so it's 見た + いる
- rule is not explained in source
- present negative: 見ない
- te form affirmative: 見て
- could be missing まだ?
#居るいる:
  • to be ...-ing; to have been ...-ing
    (Ichidan verb; Auxiliary verb; after the -te form of a verb; indicates continuing action or state; usu. written as kana)
column4: ammo/1580927708198-見なかった見ていない見ませんでした見ていません.mp3

column1: 食べなかった・まだ食べていない
column2:
Didn't eat / Haven’t eaten YET
- In affirmative sentences, まだ always corresponds to 'still'. In negative sentences, however, it corresponds to 'yet' when an action has not yet been taken
- like "still... not exist"
column4: ammo/1580927708200-食べなかったまだ食べていない.mp3

column1: まだ朝ご飯を食べていない
column2: I haven’t eaten breakfast yet.

column1: パーティーに持っていって
column2:
Take it to the party.
- itte as in 行って. Base form: 持っていく - to take (something to)
- 持っていって could be an inflection of 持つ (Te-form. It is a connective form of the verb.)
- 持っていって = 持つ + 行く
- like "take it to the party (when you go there)"?
#持つ:to hold (in one's hand); to take; to carry​
#持ってくる:to bring; to take (something) along; to fetch; to get​
column4: ammo/1581356822274-パーティーに持っていって.mp3

column2:
Wanna eat ramen? !inf
-ない can also be used as suggestion or invitation.
